, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Selby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire) and Scottish: habitational name from Selby (Yorkshire). The placename may derive from Old English <i>sele</i> ‘willow copse’, sometimes alternating with <i>salh</i> ‘willow’, + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’.","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Shelby","meanings":["English (Essex and Middlesex): probably a variant of   Selby  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Selby was born in 1119, in England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Agnes de Selby. He died on 1 May 1181, at the age of 62, and was buried in Maldon, Essex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1119–01 May 1181":"1119–1. mai 1181","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1124–Female":"1124–Surnud","1183–1216":"1183–1216","1136–Male":"1136–Surnud","1119–1181":"1119–1181","1216":"1216","1